{{Refimprove|date=March 2010}} {{Infobox artist | name = Jean-Paul Laurens | image = Laurens_-_Self portrait.jpg | imagesize = 230px | Alias = | caption = Self-portrait | birth_name = | birth_date = 28 March 1838 | birth_place = [[Fourquevaux]], [[France]] | death_date = {{d-da|23 March 1921|28 March 1838}} | death_place = [[Paris]], [[France]] | nationality = | field = [[Painting]] | training = | movement = | works = }} '''Jean-Paul Laurens''' (28 March 1838&nbsp;– 23 March 1921) was a [[France|French]] painter and [[sculptor]], and one of the last major exponents of the French [[Academic art|Academic]] style.
Laurens was born in [[Fourquevaux]] and was a pupil of [[Léon Cogniet]] and [[Alexandre Bida]]. Strongly [[anti-clericalism|anti-clerical]] and [[republicanism|republican]], his work was often on historical and religious themes, through which he sought to convey a message of opposition to monarchical and clerical oppression. His erudition and technical mastery were much admired in his time, but in later years his highly realistic technique, coupled to a theatrical ''[[mise-en-scène]]'', came to be regarded by some art-historians as overly didactic. More recently, however, his work has been re-evaluated as an important and original renewal of history painting, a genre of painting that was in decline during Laurens' lifetime.
Laurens was commissioned to paint numerous public works by the [[French Third Republic]], including the steel vault of the [[Hôtel de Ville, Paris|Paris City Hall]], the monumental series on the life of [[Genevieve|Saint Genevieve]] in the apse of the [[Panthéon, Paris|Panthéon]], the decorated ceiling of the Odéon Theater, and the hall of distinguished citizens at the [[Toulouse]] capitol. He also provided illustrations for [[Augustin Thierry]]'s ''Récits des temps mérovingiens'' ("Accounts of [[Merovingian]] Times").
Laurens was highly respected teacher at the [[Académie Julian]], Paris, and a professor at the ''[[École des Beaux-Arts|École nationale supérieure des Beaux-Arts]]'' in Paris, where he taught [[André Dunoyer de Segonzac]] and [[George Barbier (illustrator)|George Barbier]]. He died in [[Paris]], aged 82. Two of his sons, [[Paul Albert Laurens]] (1870–1934) and [[Jean-Pierre Laurens]] (1875–1932), both also became painters and teachers at the Académie Julian.
